  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose civil and criminal penalties for violations\n\n3. Implementing Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n\n4. Specific Offenses:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained money\n- Structuring transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n- Engaging in financial transactions with criminal proceeds\n\n5. International Cooperation:\n- Compliance with Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Collaboration with international law enforcement agencies\n\nThese statutes provide a comprehensive legal framework for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities in the United States.",
